# 03 — Private-VNet runners

> **Owner: central platform team.** Needed when the deployment target is on a
> private network (private endpoints, no public ingress). Public Microsoft-hosted
> runners cannot reach private endpoints, so the pipeline must run on a runner
> with a NIC in (or peered to) the target VNet.

This pilot's network exposure: **private = {{PRIVATE_NETWORK}}**.

## GitHub Actions options
- **Self-hosted runners** on a VM / VM scale set joined to the VNet — label the
  workflow `runs-on: [ self-hosted, threadlight-prod ]`.
- **GitHub-hosted larger runners with Azure private networking** — managed by
  GitHub, with a NIC injected into your VNet (a managed "larger runner" option,
  no infra to patch).

## Azure DevOps options
- **Managed DevOps Pool** with VNet injection — Microsoft-managed agents placed
  on your subnet; referenced from the pipeline as `pool: { name: <pool> }`.
- **Self-hosted agents** (VMSS agent pool) joined to the VNet.

## Provisioning sketch (self-hosted VMSS, either platform)
```bash
# Create a VNet-joined VM scale set to host self-hosted runners/agents.
az vmss create \
  --name vmss-{{ENV_NAME}}-runners \
  --resource-group {{TARGET_RESOURCE_GROUP}} \
  --subscription {{TARGET_SUBSCRIPTION_ID}} \
  --image Ubuntu2204 \
  --vnet-name <target-vnet> --subnet <runners-subnet> \
  --instance-count 2 --orchestration-mode Uniform
# Then install the GitHub runner / ADO agent and register it to the repo/pool.
```

> The platform team owns this infrastructure. The pilot pipeline only references
> the runner label / pool name — it never creates network or platform resources.
